Power to the Person
If you=E2=80=99ve spent much time on the internet recently you might have n=
oticed something: it=E2=80=99s gotten really fast-paced and really fun. It =
just keeps getting faster and funner. Bitcoin, Clubhouse, NFTs, unicorn sta=
rtups galore, the Creator Economy. Each feels simultaneously like a potenti=
al fad and a nascent revolution.
From the eye of the storm, it=E2=80=99s hard to tell exactly what it means.=
 Will digital artists continue to mint millions from NFTs? Will Creator Eco=
nomy startups continue to raise early stage rounds at dizzying valuations? =
Will consumer social apps need top-tier influencer founders to cut through =
the noise?=C2=A0
I have no idea, and instead of singling out any company or NFT, a thought e=
xercise seems more appropriate, based on three ideas that keep coming to mi=
nd:=C2=A0
A main Not Boring theme that Genies don=E2=80=99t go quietly back into bott=
les.
Chris Dixon=E2=80=99s famous line that =E2=80=9Cthe next big thing will sta=
rt out looking like a toy.=E2=80=9D
Ben Thompson=E2=80=99s idea that media businesses are the first to adapt to=
 new paradigms because of their relative simplicity, and others follow late=
r.
Taken together, what I see happening is this:=C2=A0
The Creator Economy and NFTs are massive human potential unlocks. Even if c=
ertain assets are in a short-term bubble, we are on an inexorable march tow=
ards individuals mattering more than institutions.=C2=A0
We=E2=80=99re on the precipice of a creative explosion, fueled by putting p=
ower, and the ability to generate wealth, in the hands of the people. Armed=
 with powerful technical and financial tools, individuals will be able to l=
aunch and scale increasingly complex projects and businesses. Within two de=
cades, we will have multiple trillion-plus dollar publicly traded entities =
with just one full-time employee, the founder.=20
That sounds bold, but it=E2=80=99s kind of already happened: as of last wee=
k, Bitcoin, which has no employees, crossed the $1 trillion mark.
I think that the Passion Economy broadly will continue to expand beyond med=
ia and entertainment and that we=E2=80=99ll see more and more companies -- =
some small, some big; some permanent, some temporary -- that do all of the =
things that companies do today, with one person. That doesn=E2=80=99t mean =
we=E2=80=99ll all be sitting in our basements, alone, growing rich and unha=
ppy; to the contrary, I think we=E2=80=99ll see the continued rise of colle=
ctives and communities, some lifelong and some project-specific and fleetin=
g. Some of us might even choose to work together.=C2=A0
Why does it matter that one person will be able to launch companies that ri=
val corporations in scope, scale, and innovation? Because currently, Passio=
n Economy businesses are tied to the creator. Creators, even well-paid ones=
, are still more labor than capital. If I get hit by a bus tomorrow, the co=
ntent stops, and Not Boring stops making money. We=E2=80=99re after product=
s can outlive their founders and continue to produce wealth after they=E2=
=80=99re gone.=C2=A0
People follow people, not companies, but companies have long had the advant=
age because of all of the coordination it takes to build scaled products. A=
s a result, they capture a disproportionate share of the profits. Even Crea=
tor Economy platforms like Substack and TikTok treat creators themselves as=
 commoditized supply. While people are making great livings through their w=
ork, which is a great step, I think the confluence of the Passion Economy, =
DeFi, and NFTs will mean that the creators themselves will capture the lion=
s=E2=80=99 share of the profits. I=E2=80=99m excited to see more individual=
s commoditize platforms, instead of the other way around.
We haven=E2=80=99t scratched the surface of the implications of giving the =
power to the person. Today, we=E2=80=99ll scratch.=C2=A0
